nodes.title: Note: About image size
widgets_values: You can use the latent from the **EmptySD3LatentImage** to replace **VAE Encode**, so you can customize the image size.

nodes.title: Note: KSampler settings
widgets_values:
You can test and find the best setting by yourself. The following table is for reference.

| Model            | Steps | CFG |
|---------------------|---------------|---------------|
| Offical             | 50               | 4.0               
| fp8_e4m3fn             | 20                | 2.5               |
| fp8_e4m3fn + 4steps LoRA    | 4               | 1.0               |

nodes.title: Core Parameters
widgets_values:
Crop Edge Reserve Percentage:
The amount to extend the character's crop by mask. The default is 25% works fine.

Relight / Original Character Blend:
The amount of Relight / Original mix. 
100% is all Relight.
0% is all original.
The default is 75%, but the exact value depends on the style, taste and gatcha.

nodes.title: Edge Mask Adjustments
widgets_values:
If your character or shadow contacts the edge of the full image, then the edge mask needs to be adjusted. The default option is is that the BOTTOM edge of the mask is not feathered.

If your character or shadow are completley contained and within the edge mask, then the LayerMaskTransform can be bypassed entirely. When bypassed, all four edges will be feathered. Should be fine even if it remains on, although the bottom edge seam may be visible.

If your character or shadow contacts one of the side edges as well, you can further adjust manually with '1' in X Scale and either '1' (for leftward) or '-1' (for rightward) in X Move.

Anything more complicated than that and you'll need to disconnect all non-mask connections and enter the values manually. You can run use the expanded math node results as reference numbers to work off of.

nodes.title: Upscaling
widgets_values:
Use your upscaler of choice.

If your character is only going to be on a small portion of your background, its recommended that you upscale your background enough so that the cropped image is at least 1 megapixel in size.

nodes.title: Background Image
widgets_values:
The scene to place the character in.

There should be nothing in the foreground obscuring the character.

nodes.title: Note: Raw latent version
widgets_values:
Since the **TextEncodeQwenImageEditPlus** node will scale the image to 1M pixels, you might find that the output has a pixel-shifting issue.

The **Raw latent version** is to provide the raw latent to the sampler. This is the way you can provide the raw latent as an input condition.

nodes.title: Color Match
widgets_values:
there is a 'Color Match' Node (Cyan) in the comp section. I've disabled it by default, but it helps if you feel the color is off.

For some flat-shaded styles yields blotchy colors. If you're doing photo-real, semi-real or 3d render type styles, I recommend turning it back on.

nodes.title: Prompt
widgets_values:
Here's the prompt structure, you can try improving on it if you like:

Make the lighting of [the subject] to match the lighting of the scene. [The subject] is [lit in a certain way] and [casts a shadow a certain way]. Maintain color, lighting and mood in the scene. Maintain the pose and details of [the subject].

Feel free to adjust as needed!

nodes.title: Character and Pose input images
widgets_values:
Character image:
The character should be forward-facing, and ideally with the full body visible. Otherwise its very flexible. A-pose or T-pose are not necessary.

The generated image WILL attempt to adapt to the background. Its best that the character and pose images have similar camera angles.

Qwen is very adaptable to a humanoid of any style.

Pose image:
The character should be forward-facing or side-facing, and MUST be entirely visible. The character should not be upside-down, if so, flip it over.

DW Pose is the issue here, it has a hard time recognizing weird poses and odd angles. It leans towards photo-real lighting, so take note.

Otherwise, Qwen does a good job. If you have a method of manually providing a DW Pose formatted pose image, that will work even better

Make the lighting of the woman to match the lighting of the scene. She is tinted a sickly yellow being lit by below and casts a shadow onto the scene. Maintain color, lighting and mood in the scene. Maintain the pose and details of the woman.

nodes.title: Character positioning / scale / rotation
widgets_values:
Use the red "ImageBlendAdvance" node in Preprocessing to position, scale and rotate the character.

x and y percent determines the position of the character on the background. 'scale' and 'rotation' are self-explanatory.

Performance is best IF character is standing or directly in contact with the scene, ideally with a scale and position that makes sense.
